Implemented Vercel Web Analytics for Next.js

## Changes Made

### 1. Installed @vercel/analytics package
- Added @vercel/analytics (v1.6.1) to project dependencies
- Used pnpm package manager to install the package
- Updated pnpm-lock.yaml to reflect new dependency

### 2. Integrated Analytics component in root layout
Modified: app/src/app/layout.tsx
- Imported Analytics component from '@vercel/analytics/next'
- Added <Analytics /> component inside the <body> tag, after the </Providers> closing tag
- Placed it at the end of the body to ensure optimal loading performance

## Files Modified
- app/package.json - Added @vercel/analytics dependency
- app/src/app/layout.tsx - Imported and integrated Analytics component
- pnpm-lock.yaml (parent directory) - Updated lock file with new dependency tree

## Implementation Details
This is an App Router Next.js project (using app directory structure), so the Analytics component was added to the root layout file (app/src/app/layout.tsx) as per Vercel's documentation. The component was placed at the end of the <body> tag to ensure it loads after all page content, following best practices for analytics integration.

## Verification
- ESLint passed with no warnings or errors
- All changes follow existing code structure and patterns
- Analytics will automatically track page views when deployed to Vercel

## Notes
The Analytics component will automatically start collecting page view data when the application is deployed to Vercel. No additional configuration is required. The component is designed to be zero-config and works out of the box with Vercel deployments.
